@user1:
I recall we talked about the parameter naming strategy last week, but I'm having second thoughts. I worry that introducing our own paramters prefixed with `SOCIAL_AUTH_AZUREAD` may cause confusion among users expecting to see it the `python-social-auth` docs. I don't have a better suggestion though; open to other opinions.

@user2:
Why not prefix with `NETBOX_`?

@author:
changed to REMOTE_AUTH_BACKEND_ and auto-imported everything starting with this as we will probably be adding more so can group them all together.

@user1:
There doesn't seem to be any error handling in place. At a minimum, we should catch any fatal errors and re-raise them with some context for the user. Some comments would also be helpful to explain what requests are being made and why.

Additionally, we should avoid declaring `url` multiple times: If the value isn't being reused, we can pass the string(s) directly to `requests.get()` instead.

@author:
For error checking I think the error from the API call would contain the most info so I've added extra logging but re-raise the error.
